<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="product-discovery">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>product</group>
    <domain>product-manager</domain>
    <summary>De-risk ideas by testing Value, Usability, Feasibility, and Business Viability. Map assumptions, design cheap-to-fail experiments with kill thresholds, run 1-2 at once, timebox 1-4 weeks.</summary>
    <category>discovery</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
      <tag>validation</tag>
      <tag>experimentation</tag>
      <tag>risk-management</tag>
      <tag>assumptions</tag>
    </tags>
    <tools>
      <tool>claude-code</tool>
    </tools>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Product Discovery</title>

    <summary>Systematically de-risk ideas before committing engineering capacity by testing four risk types: Value (will customers use it?), Usability (can they figure it out?), Feasibility (can we build it?), and Business Viability (does it work for the business?). Map all assumptions, tag each by risk type and severity, then design the cheapest experiment that could falsify the highest-severity assumption first. Every experiment requires a hypothesis, a success threshold, and an explicit kill threshold. Timebox each discovery cycle to 1-4 weeks.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Teams that skip discovery build features nobody wants and discover problems after launch. The four-risk framework forces prioritization of dangerous assumptions over easy ones — the lethal risk is almost never the most comfortable one to test. Cheap-to-fail experiments (prototypes over code, scripts over services, fakes over builds) mean the cost of being wrong is a week of time, not a quarter of engineering.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before committing engineering capacity to a new feature, product, or market segment.</item>
        <item>When a stakeholder request lacks evidence and needs a structured assumption test.</item>
        <item>After analytics flags a divergence (drop-off, churn) and the team needs root cause before solutioning.</item>
        <item>When entering an unfamiliar domain where all four risks are unknown.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure execution work where all four risks are already addressed by existing evidence.</item>
        <item>Time-bounded compliance or contractual deliverables — discovery cannot move the deadline.</item>
        <item>Trivial features (less than 2 days) where running an experiment costs more than building.</item>
        <item>When the team will not act on results — discovery without decision power is theatre.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="four-risk-types">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before designing any experiment, classify every assumption into exactly one of four risk types: Value (will customers use it?), Usability (can they figure it out?), Feasibility (can we build it?), Business Viability (does it work for the business?). Sort assumptions by risk type and severity before selecting methods.</statement>
        <rationale>Teams that skip risk classification default to testing easy assumptions (often Usability) while ignoring lethal ones (often Value or Business Viability). The classification forces the conversation about which risk would kill the idea if wrong.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="value-risk-techniques">
      <p>Ordered by increasing effort and confidence: customer interviews (low effort, medium confidence), surveys (low effort, low confidence), fake-door tests (low effort, medium confidence), landing page tests (low effort, medium confidence), concierge MVP (medium effort, high confidence), Wizard of Oz (medium effort, high confidence).</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Combine at least two Value-risk methods before concluding validation. Surveys alone are insufficient — users say one thing and do another.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-method value validation is the most common source of false positives in product discovery.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="usability-risk-techniques">
      <p>Paper prototypes (low effort, low confidence), clickable prototypes (medium effort, medium confidence), moderated usability testing (medium effort, high confidence), A/B testing (high effort, very high confidence).</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use A/B testing only for optimization of existing surfaces, not for validating new concepts. For new concepts, prototype testing is the appropriate method.</statement>
        <rationale>A/B tests require sufficient traffic and a working implementation. Running them for concept validation burns engineering time that prototype testing avoids.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="feasibility-risk-techniques">
      <p>Technical spike (low-medium effort, high confidence), architecture review (low effort, medium confidence), proof of concept (medium effort, high confidence), vendor evaluation (low effort, medium confidence).</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a technical spike before committing any assumption tagged feasibility=hi to delivery planning. A spike costs days; a wrong feasibility assumption costs a quarter.</statement>
        <rationale>Feasibility assumptions are the most underchecked risk type because engineers feel confident and PMs defer to them. A spike creates an explicit evidence artifact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="severity-first-selection-rule">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always test the highest-severity assumption first, regardless of how easy a lower-severity test would be. The lethal risk is the one that would kill the idea if wrong; test it before investing in anything else.</statement>
        <rationale>Teams default to testing the most comfortable assumption. Explicit severity-first sorting overrides that bias.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="bad" title="Testing usability before value">
        <note>Team has high-severity Value risk and medium-severity Usability risk. They run a usability test first because they have a prototype ready. Value assumption is never tested. Feature ships to zero adoption.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="five-step-discovery-process">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>List every assumption the proposal makes — about user behaviour, willingness to pay, technical feasibility, and business model. No assumption is too obvious to list; obvious assumptions are often the ones that fail.</statement>
        <rationale>Undocumented assumptions cannot be validated. The act of listing them surfaces disagreements among team members before experiments are designed.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sort assumptions by: severity (hi/md/lo) first, then effort to test (lo/md/hi) second. Focus the discovery sprint on the top 2-3 high-severity assumptions only.</statement>
        <rationale>Trying to validate all assumptions simultaneously dilutes effort. Discovery must converge on the assumptions that would kill the idea if wrong.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every experiment must specify: hypothesis ("If X then Y by Z%"), method, audience, sample size (with justification), duration, success threshold, and kill threshold. An experiment without a kill threshold cannot teach.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a pre-set kill threshold, confirmation bias wins — teams always find a way to interpret results as partial validation. Kill thresholds force honest decision-making.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Design experiments to falsify, not to confirm. For every proposed experiment, ask: "If this assumption is wrong, would this experiment catch it?" If no, redesign.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents and PMs default to confirmation-seeking designs. An explicit falsification test in the design step prevents the most common discovery error.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap at 1-2 active experiments per discovery cycle. Additional experiments go into a queue, not active execution.</statement>
        <rationale>Running too many experiments simultaneously makes causation impossible to attribute and splits team focus.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep experiments cheap: prototypes over code, scripts over services, fakes over builds. Never run production code during discovery.</statement>
        <rationale>Building during discovery defeats the cheap-fail principle. Production code creates sunk-cost pressure that biases the go/no-go decision.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Document all learnings (including null results) in a research repository. Undocumented null results cause the same experiment to be run again in the next cycle.</statement>
        <rationale>Discovery without memory repeats itself. Null results are evidence; they are as valuable as positive results for constraining the solution space.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Final go/no-go is a human decision. The decision signals are: all critical risks addressed (Proceed), lethal risk not validated (Pivot or Kill), partial validation (More Discovery needed). Timebox "More Discovery" to prevent perpetual stalling.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs may flag Proceed on weak evidence because they cannot weigh business consequence. Human ownership of the final decision is non-negotiable.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="discovery-antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Discovery cycle extends beyond 4 weeks with the justification "we need more data".</description>
        <reason>Permanent stalling disguised as discovery is a decision avoidance pattern. Hard timeboxing forces the team to decide with the evidence at hand.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A risk-mapper agent reads the proposal and emits an assumption matrix tagging each by risk type (value/usability/feasibility/business) and severity. A method-picker agent matches each high-risk assumption to a discovery technique using the technique tables. An experiment-designer agent drafts hypothesis + method + success/kill criteria + sample size. After each experiment finishes, a synthesizer agent updates the matrix and recommends Proceed / Pivot / Kill / More Discovery. Humans run user-facing experiments and own the final go/no-go decision.</p>

      <list>
        <item>faion-idea-generator-agent — referenced; designs experiments and brainstorms tests.</item>
        <item>faion-mvp-scope-analyzer-agent — translates a "Proceed" decision into MVP scope.</item>
        <item>faion-spec-reviewer-agent — reviews experiment designs for falsifiability and ethical issues.</item>
        <item>faion-task-creator-agent — converts experiments into trackable backlog items with owners.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents proposing only happy-path validation; force a "design an experiment to falsify this" prompt variant.</item>
        <item>Hallucinated sample sizes ("100 users should be enough"). Demand a power-calculation justification or a published rule-of-thumb.</item>
        <item>LLMs cannot run interviews or read body language; treat their interview "synthesis" as theme extraction, never as conclusion.</item>
        <item>Confirmation bias loop: agent reads the proposal, generates "supportive" assumptions, then "validates" them. Inject a critic role.</item>
        <item>Without explicit ethics check, agents propose dark patterns (deceptive landing pages, hidden charges) — add a refusal clause for deceptive practices.</item>
        <item>Multi-experiment plans pile up; cap at 1–2 active experiments per discovery cycle, mark others "queued".</item>
        <item>Survey-bias inflation — agents recommend surveys for everything because they are cheap; require behavioural evidence as a tiebreaker.</item>
        <item>Token cost: a full assumption matrix + experiment slate ≈ 6–10k tokens output. Prune by risk severity, not exhaustively.</item>
        <item>Final go/no-go must be human; the LLM may flag "Proceed" on weak evidence because it cannot weigh business consequence.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Map risks before designing experiments. Skipping the matrix leads to easy-but-irrelevant tests.</item>
        <item>Allocate 20–30% of total team capacity to discovery, not "leftover time".</item>
        <item>Combine methods to triangulate: interview signals + behavioural metric + a quantitative survey or fake-door test.</item>
        <item>Always set a kill threshold; an experiment without a failure condition cannot teach.</item>
        <item>Timebox each discovery cycle to 1–4 weeks; longer cycles signal scope creep.</item>
        <item>Document assumptions, evidence, and decisions in a single research repository (Dovetail, Notion). Discovery without memory repeats itself.</item>
        <item>Cheap to fail: prototypes over code, scripts over services, fakes over builds.</item>
        <item>Pair discovery with mvp-scoping: the MVP slice should aim to validate the next dangerous assumption, not ship a feature.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <p>CLI tools for discovery: posthog API (run feature flags + cohort experiments), growthbook (OSS feature flagging + experimentation), unleash (OSS feature flag service), optimizely-cli (manage A/B tests programmatically), maze API (rapid prototype tests), userinterviews API (recruit participants programmatically), whisper (OpenAI; transcribe interview audio), dovetail API (push tagged research notes), gsheets/gspread (cheap experiment log).</p>

      <p>Services (SaaS/OSS, agent-friendly): Maze (unmoderated prototype + concept tests), Useberry (cheaper Maze alternative), User Interviews (recruitment for interviews), Dovetail (synthesis + tagging), Lookback (live moderated sessions; recordings via API), GrowthBook (self-host A/B + feature flag platform), PostHog (analytics + experiments + feature flags), Optimizely (enterprise A/B platform), Typeform (quick concierge surveys / fake-door tests), Carrd / Framer (stand up landing pages for value tests).</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/discovery-kickoff.md" purpose="Discovery session template: context, team, core questions, assumption matrix, success criteria."/>
      <template path="templates/experiment-report.md" purpose="Experiment report: hypothesis, setup, results table, learnings, decision."/>
      <template path="templates/validate-experiment.py" purpose="Python gate: verifies experiment has hypothesis, kill threshold, sample size, and a power-calculation check."/>
    </templates>

